Last month, the Proteas opted not to take the knee during their series against England. AFP/Rodger Bosch JOHANNESBURG - Cricket South Africa's interim board says criticism levelled at the Proteas for not taking the knee, is justified. Last month, the Proteas opted not to take the knee during their series against England. Instead, they declared that the team was exploring the significance of the gesture and of a raised fist. READ: Racial divisions laid bare in SA cricket The CSA interim board says that decision was ill-conceived, given the history of racial injustice in South Africa. Chairperson Justice Zak Yacoob said it was an opportunity to show the world that we're united in opposing racism at every turn. The Proteas play Sri Lanka in two tests, starting next Saturday.